2. Differences in Delta T

By making use of the box plot, now it is explored how different values for delta t affect the data.

2.1 Interpretation of data

As we can see the smaller delta t, the more variation we also have in the data. This is due to measurement errors which add up if you collect data within smaller periods of time.

In general, when it comes to the pros and cons of delta t, a few of the following are worth mentioning:

Pros:

  1. Less data storage required: With a higher value of delta t, there will be fewer data points to store, which can save storage space and reduce the cost of data storage.
  2. Less processing power required: With fewer data points to process, less processing power may be required for data analysis.
  3. May be sufficient for certain applications: In some cases, a higher value of delta t may be sufficient for the needs of the application. For example, if the data is being used to monitor long-term trends, a lower time resolution may be adequate.

Cons:

  1. Reduced accuracy: A higher value of delta t means that data is being collected less frequently, which can result in a loss of accuracy. If there are rapid changes or fluctuations in the data that are missed due to the coarser time resolution, the resulting analysis may be less accurate.
  2. Missed events: With a higher value of delta t, it is possible that important events or changes may be missed if they occur between measurements. This can be a significant issue in applications where real-time monitoring is necessary.
  3. Limited ability for analysis: With a coarser time resolution, it may be more difficult to identify patterns or trends in the data that would be evident with a finer time resolution. Explanation what colour stands for what activity.

3. Outlier detection with dbscan

In the following section outliers tried to be detected using the dbscan library. In this code snippet, the kNNdistplot function is used to visualize the k-nearest neighbor distances of the data points in the dataset data. The k parameter is set to 4.5, which means that the distances of each point to its 4.5 nearest neighbors will be computed.

The purpose of using the kNNdistplot function is to determine a good value for the eps parameter in the dbscan clustering algorithm, which is used to cluster the data points. The eps parameter specifies the maximum distance between two points in the same cluster, and the MinPts parameter specifies the minimum number of points required to form a dense region in the cluster.

The kNNdistplot function generates a plot that shows the distribution of k-nearest neighbor distances. By visually inspecting the plot, one can identify a “knee” or elbow point in the curve where the rate of change of the distances becomes more gradual. This knee point can be used as a threshold to determine a good value for the eps parameter.

In the code, the knee point is estimated to be at a distance of 4.5, which is marked on the plot with a red line using the abline function. This value is then used as the eps parameter in the dbscan function to cluster the data points. Any points that do not belong to any cluster are considered outliers and are highlighted in red in the final plot.

The same method is applied to find outliers in all the other columns of the dataset (=different sensors).

In total outliers have been detected in 27 different rows. Since this is only around 2% of the whole dataset the rows of the outliers will just be deleted.

4. Feature engineering - Temporal Aggregation of data

In the following example the approach of feature engineering in a time domain was chosen. For each column of the acceleration dimension the change was calculated. Then, the different changes were combined into one column (avg_change_Acc), after that the “rolling_sum” was calculated, which is the sum of the previous 10 entries. Since there are many different columns e.g., acceleration in 3 different dimensions, it might make sense to combine these different columns into one column summarizing the overall change that takes place. Besides other advantages, this might lead to less computing power needed to process all the data.

5. PCA to get a better understanding of the data

In order to get a better understanding of my data and see which variables contribute the most in conducted a PCA. I excluded several column (Activity type, index and time), since they would not be meaningful and only distort the outcome.

In PCA, the scree plot is a graphical representation of the eigenvalues of the principal components. The elbow method is a common approach used in Principal Component Analysis (PCA) to determine the optimal number of principal components to retain for further analysis. It involves plotting the eigenvalues of each principal component in descending order and identifying the “elbow point” on the scree plot, which is the point where the rate of decrease in explained variance slows down. This point indicates the optimal number of principal components to retain in the analysis. In my analysis, the elbow point was identified after the second principal component, indicating that the first two principal components contain the majority of the information in the dataset. Therefore, I decided to only keep the first two principal components for further analysis, as they are the most important in explaining the variability in the data.

In the following graph it is depicted which variables contribute how much to the first principal component. As shown in the graphs the rolling sum column does not contribute a lot to explain the variance.
